<h4>That LTR</h4>

<p>
	When you’re raising money for your startup, did you know that a long term relationship also comes with the money? Yep. 7-10 years, even.
</p>

<p>
	Here are 4 things you need to know about this relationship lifecycle. Tyler Peterson of Triangle Peak Partners comments on 4 key phases - dating, marriage, those “happy days”, and the break up.
</p>


<h4>About Tyler Peterson and Triangle Peak Partners</h4>

<p>
	Tyler is Google alumni who spent much of his career on Sheryl Sandberg’s analyst team in the earlier years of the company. Tyler’s position at Google led him to do internal consulting and strategy work for a number of businesses inside Google. With his experience of working on a variety of strategy projects for products such as AdWords and Google Checkout, it’s no surprise Tyler now serves as Vice President at Triangle Peak Partners.
</p>

<p>
	Triangle Peak Partners is a venture firm focused on tech, as well as private equity and growth equity in energy. They are active in all sectors of tech including enterprise software, marketplaces, and ad tech. Triangle Peak primarily invests in companies already generating revenue and raising their series B or later. They invest in a small number of seed deals as well.
</p>

<h4>Phase 1 - Dating</h4>

<p>
	Going out and finding venture capital can be as exhilarating as Tinder swiping right for the first time. There are, however, some things first timers should take into consideration.
</p>

<p>
	There is a perception that if a VC invests in a competitor, they will be interested in your startup too, but this is false. Tyler says this is the one common mistake many first time entrepreneurs make. Trying to “date” a VC who has invested in a competitor is a no-no.
</p>

<p>
	“If an entrepreneur is smart, they will look at a VC’s portfolio before they pitch. They should be thinking about their competitors and if there is a conflict of interest.” Tyler says.
</p>

<p>
	If you have a similar company not in direct competition with a VC’s portfolio company, that is great because it demonstrates that the VC understands your space, but if you are in direct competition with someone they have already invested in, it’s best to stay away.
</p>

<h4>Phase 2 - Getting Married</h4>

