	<img src="img/articles/lego-marriage.jpg" alt="Lego Marriage">
</p>

<h5 class="margin-top text-center">
	“We’ve passed on investments we liked because personalities did not line up”.
</h5>

<p class="margin-top">
	“The VC business is a relationship business.” says Tyler. “And as a founder/CEO raising money, you should be thinking about how much easier it is to fire an employee than it is an investor on your board.”
</p>

<p>
	Tyler stresses the importance of building trust early on in the relationship and having a good rapport.
</p>

<p>
	Entrepreneurs getting “married” to investors would be wise to heed this advice. If you can’t communicate with someone before you begin a relationship that may last a decade, imagine what the communication will (or won’t) be like when you hit that trough of disillusionment.
</p>

<h4>Phase 3 - Those “Happy Days”</h4>

<p>
	When things get bumpy in a relationship, it’s always a challenge to figure out how two parties are going to interact with each other and get through the tough times. In the VC/entrepreneur relationship, there are certain things VCs expect from the entrepreneur.
</p>

<p>
	“In the venture world, it’s always the companies that are performing badly that are taking up 90% of your time. And when a company is not going well, we expect honesty and full disclosure.” says Tyler.
</p>

<p>
	Tyler illustrates an example of what a relationship may look like if a company is failing. The company may go through a period of fast testing with 30 day iterative cycles and communicate results to the board. If the company fails to make their 30 day goals, then discussions happen about next steps.
</p>

<h4>Phase 4 - The Breakup</h4>

<p>
	“When it is time for a Founder/CEO to move on from the company, it can be a very upsetting time for them, but there are millions of dollars at stake and different constituencies that need to be considered.” says Tyler. This is often an extremely difficult thing to hear for a Founder/CEO and often a hard realization to come to.
</p>

<p>	
	Tyler recalls a company that was doing well but not amazing. The board thought the company could be doing better and was making suggestions, but the CEO was not budging. Because the entire board was aligned on one side and the CEO was on the other, the CEO was inevitably fired.
</p>

<p>
	I can imagine how difficult it is for a Founder/CEO to have to give up leading a company they started, but it is also crucial that founders, when time, come to terms with what may be best for the overall success of the company.
</p>

